## What Surprised Me (The Good)

The time optimization aspect of the MED principle is completely sound. 

Because the workouts themselves were wrapped up in under 20 minutes, I suddenly had a massive surplus of time on my hands. I used that extra time to add **3x weekly sauna sessions** directly after leaving the floor. 

Even though I was spending a fraction of my usual time in the gym, I left every session feeling as though I had done a complete, heavy workout. The deep fatigue from taking a single set to true failure on a 10-second rep cycle is no joke. You save time, but you pay for it in pure intensity.

---

## The Reality Check (The Bad & The Ugly)

While the time-saving principle works, the real-world execution ran into two massive roadblocks for me.

### 1. The Age Factor & Injury
During Week 2, I strained my shoulder during the machine shoulder press. Taking heavy compound movements to absolute mechanical failure at a grindingly slow pace places an enormous amount of stress on your connective tissues. 

Let's be completely honest: this protocol is highly geared toward younger gym-goers whose joints and tendons are highly forgiving. As a 45-year-old training with longevity and healthspan in mind, the risk-to-reward ratio here simply doesn't balance out. An injury that sets you back weeks completely defeats the purpose of optimization.

### 2. The Vegan Nutrition Gap
The other massive hurdle was the diet. Tim Ferriss pairs this protocol with a massive caloric surplus and a hyper-strict Slow-Carb Diet. 

As a vegan, sticking to the rigidity of the Slow-Carb framework while trying to hit massive protein targets without grains or dairy is incredibly difficult. On top of that, I am currently limiting my intake to around 2,000 calories a day. Trying to build mass on a protocol explicitly designed for a hyper-caloric surplus while operating in a deficit heavily muted any potential results.

